|YK0SYNTAX
======
|YKBhelp colors|YK0

|YK0DESCRIPTION
===========
Darkwind supports several ways to color text in places where player
customization allows it, such as channel colors and some display settings.

The traditional Darkwind color code is three characters after a | symbol.
In the examples below, remove the space after | when using the code:

  |YKB| YKB|YK0  yellow text, black background, bold
  |YKB| RK0|YK0  red text, black background, normal
  |YKB| XX0|YK0  reset to normal

The three positions mean:

  1. foreground color
  2. background color
  3. effect

Common foreground and background letters are:

  |YK0K|XX0 black     |YK0R|XX0 red       |YK0G|XX0 green
  |YK0Y|XX0 yellow    |YK0B|XX0 blue      |YK0M|XX0 magenta
  |YK0C|XX0 cyan      |YK0W|XX0 white     |YK0X|XX0 unchanged

Common effect letters are:

  |YK0B|XX0 bold      |YK0U|XX0 underline |YK0K|XX0 blink
  |YK00|XX0 normal    |YK0O|XX0 normal

Modern clients, including Darkflow, also support expanded color markup:

  |YKB| [fg=#ff8800,bg=black,bold]orange bold text| 000|YK0
  |YKB| [fg=bright-cyan,bg=black,italic]italic cyan text| 000|YK0

Expanded markup allows truecolor hex values like |YKB#ff8800|YK0 and text
effects such as italic, strikethrough, fraktur, double-underline, hidden,
and overline when the client can display them.

|YK0USEFUL COMMANDS
===============
  |YKBtruecolor|YK0
    Shows gradients of common truecolor hex values from dark to bright.
    Use this when you want to pick a specific color.

  |YKBansieffects|YK0
    Shows the ANSI text effects supported by modern terminals and Darkflow.
    Use this when you want to test italics, hidden text, strikethrough,
    fraktur, double underline, overline, and related effects.

  |YKBcolor|YK0
    Sets channel colors. See |YKBhelp color|YK0 for syntax.

  |YKBset term|YK0
    Sets your terminal type. See |YKBhelp set|YK0 for more settings.

|YK0NOTES
=====
Not every telnet client displays every color or text effect the same way.
If something looks strange, try |YKBtruecolor|YK0 and |YKBansieffects|YK0 from
your current client to see what it supports.
